# ICPEP CITU - Environment Example and Setup Guide
# DO NOT COMMIT SECRETS: This file is a template with placeholders only. Never commit your real `.env`.

# Quick overview
# - Copy this file to `.env` in the repository root (or `server/.env` if you prefer per-service env files)
# - Fill in real secrets (Mongo URI, JWT secret, Cloudinary keys) on your machine only
# - The repository uses these variables in local dev and Docker Compose

# -----------------------------
# Root / Docker environment variables (used by docker-compose)
# -----------------------------
# Example values below are placeholders. Replace each value with your own.
PORT=5000
MONGO_URI=mongodb://localhost:27017/icpep_db
JWT_SECRET=replace_with_a_secure_random_string

# Cloudinary (optional in development; used for image uploads)
CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME=your_cloud_name
CLOUDINARY_API_KEY=your_api_key
CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET=your_api_secret

# -----------------------------
# Client-side environment (Next.js public variables)
# -----------------------------
# These are read by the client and must be prefixed with NEXT_PUBLIC_
NEXT_PUBLIC_BACKEND_URL=http://localhost:5000
NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://localhost:5000/api

# -----------------------------
# Useful step-by-step for teammates (PowerShell)
# -----------------------------
# 1) Install dependencies (run from repo root):
#
#   npm install
#   npm --prefix server install
#   npm --prefix client install
#
# 2) Create a local .env file from this template (PowerShell):
#
#   Copy-Item .env.example .env
#
#   Or, if you prefer a service-specific env (server):
#   Copy-Item .env.example server\.env
#
# 3) Edit `.env` or `server/.env` and replace placeholders with real values.
#    - For `MONGO_URI` you can use a local MongoDB URI or a cloud provider (Atlas). Example local: mongodb://localhost:27017/icpep_db
#    - Generate a JWT secret: use a secure random string (at least 32 bytes). Example generator (PowerShell):
#
#      -join ((48..57) + (65..90) + (97..122) | Get-Random -Count 64 | ForEach-Object {[char]$_})
#
# 4) Start both dev servers locally (root):
#
#   npm run dev
#
#   This will run the server and client concurrently:
#     - server: http://localhost:5000 (default)
#     - client: http://localhost:3000
#
# 5) If a port is already in use, set a different PORT environment variable before starting:
#
#   # Example: change server port to 5001 for this session (PowerShell)
#   $env:PORT=5001; npm --prefix server run dev
#
#   # Example: change Next.js dev port to 3001 for this session (PowerShell)
#   $env:PORT=3001; npm --prefix client run dev
#
# 6) Docker Compose (optional): docker-compose uses the root `.env` by default (see `docker-compose.yml`)
#
#   docker compose up --build
#
# Notes and best practices
# - Do NOT commit your `.env` file. Add it to `.gitignore` (the repo likely already ignores it).
# - Commit a `.env.example` (this file) so teammates know required variables.
# - If you need shared dev credentials, provide them out-of-band (secure chat) or use a secrets manager.
# - If you run into EADDRINUSE errors, ensure no other service (including Docker Desktop) is binding the ports 3000/5000.

# End of .env.example
# check dc server for the values
# add these files to both .env file in the root and server folder
PORT=5000
MONGO_URI=
NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://localhost:5000
JWT_SECRET=
CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME=
CLOUDINARY_API_KEY=
CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET=

# For client
# NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://localhost:5000/api